## Adding Tests to Zero-Coverage Legacy Code

### Step 1 — Characterization Tests: Pin the Existing Behaviour

Before changing anything, capture what the system actually does — bugs and all.

```java
// CharacterizationTest: records the CURRENT output, not the intended output
@SpringBootTest
@Testcontainers
class PaymentServiceCharacterizationTest {

    @Container
    static PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:15")
        .withDatabaseName("payment_test")
        .withInitScript("schema.sql");  // real schema, not H2 workaround

    @Autowired
    private PaymentService paymentService;

    @Test
    @Sql("/test-data/existing-orders.sql")  // seed realistic data
    void processPayment_existingBehaviour_noRegression() {
        PaymentRequest req = new PaymentRequest("order-123", new BigDecimal("99.99"), "USD");

        // 1. Call the method — capture whatever it returns today
        PaymentResult result = paymentService.processPayment(req);

        // 2. Approve the output (first run writes the golden file; CI reads and compares)
        Approvals.verify(result.toString());

        // 3. Every subsequent run fails if the output changes unexpectedly
        assertThat(result.getStatus()).isNotNull();
        assertThat(result.getTransactionId()).isNotBlank();
    }
}
```

### Step 2 — Find a Seam: Inject Test Doubles Without Refactoring

```java
// The legacy service hard-wires a gateway — this is our seam
public class PaymentService {
    // Previously: new PaymentGatewayClient() — impossible to test
    // Introduce constructor injection WITHOUT changing any other code
    private final PaymentGatewayClient gatewayClient;

    public PaymentService(PaymentGatewayClient gatewayClient) {
        this.gatewayClient = gatewayClient;
    }
    // ... existing methods unchanged
}
```

```java
// Spring config wires the real client in production
@Configuration
public class PaymentConfig {
    @Bean
    public PaymentGatewayClient gatewayClient() { return new StripeGatewayClient(); }
    @Bean
    public PaymentService paymentService(PaymentGatewayClient client) {
        return new PaymentService(client);
    }
}
```

```java
// Test now controls the external call
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class PaymentServiceUnitTest {
    @Mock PaymentGatewayClient gatewayClient;
    @InjectMocks PaymentService paymentService;

    @Test
    void processPayment_gatewayReturnsDeclined_setsStatusToFailed() {
        when(gatewayClient.charge(any())).thenReturn(new GatewayResponse("DECLINED", null));

        PaymentResult result = paymentService.processPayment(validRequest());

        assertThat(result.getStatus()).isEqualTo(PaymentStatus.FAILED);
        assertThat(result.getTransactionId()).isNull();
    }
}
```

### Step 3 — Write the New Feature Test-First

```java
// RED: write the test for the new feature (partial refunds) — it fails because code doesn't exist
@Test
void refundPayment_partialAmount_updatesBalanceAndPublishesEvent() {
    // Given: an existing successful payment
    PaymentRecord existing = paymentRepository.save(PaymentRecord.successful("txn-456", "99.99"));

    // When: partial refund
    RefundResult result = paymentService.refundPayment(existing.getId(), new BigDecimal("25.00"));

    // Then: balance updated, event published
    assertThat(result.getRefundedAmount()).isEqualByComparingTo("25.00");
    assertThat(result.getRemainingBalance()).isEqualByComparingTo("74.99");
    verify(eventPublisher).publish(argThat(e -> e.getType().equals("PARTIAL_REFUND")));
}

// GREEN: write the minimum code to make it pass
// REFACTOR: clean up without breaking the test
```

### Test Isolation — Reset Between Tests

```java
@SpringBootTest
@Testcontainers
@Transactional  // rolls back after each test — DB stays clean
class PaymentServiceIntegrationTest {
    // No @BeforeEach cleanup needed — @Transactional rollback handles it
}

// Alternative for tests that need committed data (e.g., async events):
@BeforeEach
void setUp() {
    paymentRepository.deleteAll();
    eventStore.clear();
}
```

### Two Weeks Execution Plan

```
Days 1-2:   Set up Testcontainers, write characterization tests for the 3 core flows
Days 3-4:   Find seams, add constructor injection, unlock unit testing
Days 5-8:   Write new feature TDD (red → green → refactor)
Days 9-10:  Contract tests for the API this service exposes
Days 11-14: Coverage gate in CI — new code must reach 80%; legacy is pinned by characterization tests
```

followUps.answer:
Four root causes of flaky integration tests and their fixes:

**1. Shared DB state between tests** — use `@Transactional` rollback, or `@Sql` with `executionPhase = AFTER_TEST_METHOD` to clean up. Never use a shared static dataset that tests mutate.

**2. Port/container race conditions** — Testcontainers' `@Container` with `static` ensures one container per test class. Use `@DynamicPropertySource` to inject the real port:

```java
@DynamicPropertySource
static void props(DynamicPropertyRegistry registry) {
    registry.add("spring.datasource.url", postgres::getJdbcUrl);
    registry.add("spring.datasource.username", postgres::getUsername);
}
```

**3. Time-dependent assertions** — avoid `Thread.sleep()`. Use Awaitility for async operations:

```java
await().atMost(5, SECONDS).until(() -> eventStore.findByType("PAYMENT_PROCESSED").isPresent());
```

**4. Test ordering dependency** — each test must set up its own preconditions. Never rely on test A running before test B. Add `@TestMethodOrder(MethodOrderer.Random.class)` in CI to catch these during development.

**Integration tests with mocks** verify that your code calls the right methods — but they can't tell you whether the real downstream service honours that contract. If the provider changes their API, mocked tests still pass and the bug reaches production.

**Contract testing (Pact)** captures the consumer's expectations as a contract, then verifies the real provider satisfies it — independently, without both services needing to run together.

```java
// Consumer side (payment-service) — defines the contract
@ExtendWith(PactConsumerTestExt.class)
class GatewayClientContractTest {
    @Pact(consumer = "payment-service", provider = "gateway-service")
    RequestResponsePact chargePact(PactDslWithProvider builder) {
        return builder.given("card is valid")
            .uponReceiving("a charge request")
            .path("/v1/charges").method("POST")
            .body(new PactDslJsonBody().decimalType("amount").stringType("currency"))
            .willRespondWith().status(200)
            .body(new PactDslJsonBody().stringType("transactionId").stringMatcher("status", "SUCCESS|DECLINED"))
            .toPact();
    }

    @Test
    @PactTestFor(pactMethod = "chargePact")
    void chargeCard_validCard_returnsTransactionId(MockServer mockServer) {
        GatewayClient client = new GatewayClient(mockServer.getUrl());
        GatewayResponse response = client.charge(new ChargeRequest("99.99", "USD"));
        assertThat(response.getTransactionId()).isNotBlank();
    }
}
```

Use contract tests for: inter-team APIs, frequently changing providers, and when spinning up both services together is slow or complex.

