## Cutting CI from 47 Minutes to Under 10

### Step 1 — Measure Before Cutting

```bash
# Find the 10 slowest test classes
mvn test -Dsurefire.reportFormat=plain 2>&1 | grep -E '\[INFO\] Tests run' | \
  sort -t',' -k4 -rn | head -10

# Output:
# PaymentIntegrationTest: 8m 23s  (PostgreSQL + Redis + Kafka all spinning up)
# OrderSagaTest:          6m 11s  (Testcontainers for every test METHOD, not class)
# ReportGenerationTest:   4m 45s  (generates 10MB PDF in every test)
```

### Step 2 — Tag Tests by Speed

```java
// Annotations
@Target(ElementType.TYPE)
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
@Tag("fast")
public @interface FastTest {}

@Target(ElementType.TYPE)
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
@Tag("integration")
public @interface IntegrationTest {}

// Usage
@FastTest
class PaymentCalculatorTest { ... }   // pure unit, no Spring context

@IntegrationTest
class PaymentServiceIntegrationTest { ... }  // Testcontainers DB
```

```xml
<!-- Maven Surefire: run only @fast tests by default -->
<plugin>
  <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
  <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
  <configuration>
    <groups>fast</groups>  <!-- excludes integration -->
  </configuration>
</plugin>

<!-- Failsafe: run integration tests in verify phase -->
<plugin>
  <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
  <artifactId>maven-failsafe-plugin</artifactId>
  <configuration>
    <groups>integration</groups>
  </configuration>
</plugin>
```

### Step 3 — Parallel Execution for Unit Tests

```properties
# src/test/resources/junit-platform.properties
junit.jupiter.execution.parallel.enabled=true
junit.jupiter.execution.parallel.mode.default=concurrent
junit.jupiter.execution.parallel.config.strategy=dynamic
junit.jupiter.execution.parallel.config.dynamic.factor=2
# 2 × availableProcessors threads; tune based on CI machine size
```

```java
// Annotate classes safe to run in parallel (stateless, no shared mutable state)
@Execution(ExecutionMode.CONCURRENT)
class PaymentCalculatorTest {
    // Each test creates its own objects — safe for parallel
}

// Integration tests with shared Testcontainers container must stay sequential
// The container is static — concurrent tests still share one DB instance
@Execution(ExecutionMode.SAME_THREAD)
@IntegrationTest
class PaymentServiceIntegrationTest {
    @Container
    static PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres = ...;  // shared across tests in this class
}
```

### Step 4 — Fix the Slow Testcontainers Anti-Pattern

```java
// BAD: new container per TEST METHOD — 8 minutes
class PaymentIntegrationTest {
    @Container  // not static → spins up AND tears down for each @Test
    PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:15");
}

// GOOD: one container per TEST CLASS — 45 seconds
class PaymentIntegrationTest {
    @Container  // static → starts once, shared across all @Test methods
    static PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:15");
    // Use @Transactional rollback or @BeforeEach cleanup instead
}

// BEST for many test classes: Singleton container pattern
public abstract class BaseIntegrationTest {
    static PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres;
    static {
        postgres = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:15");
        postgres.start();  // starts once for entire JVM lifetime
    }
}
```

### Step 5 — CI Pipeline Split

```yaml
# .github/workflows/ci.yml
jobs:
  fast-tests:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - uses: actions/cache@v3
        with:
          path: ~/.m2
          key: ${{ runner.os }}-maven-${{ hashFiles('pom.xml') }}
      - run: mvn test -Dgroups=fast -T 2C  # 2 threads per CPU core
    # Runs in ~3 minutes on every commit

  integration-tests:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: fast-tests
    if: github.event_name == 'pull_request'
    steps:
      - run: mvn verify -Dgroups=integration  # only on PR
    # Runs in ~7 minutes, only when merging
```

### Results

```
Before:  47 minutes — single pipeline, all tests, no parallelism
After:
  Every commit:  fast tests (unit, parallel) = 3m 20s
  PR merge:      fast + integration (parallelized containers) = 8m 45s
  Engineers now run fast tests locally in ~90 seconds via pre-commit hook
```

### Pre-commit Hook

```bash
# .git/hooks/pre-commit
#!/bin/bash
echo "Running fast tests..."
mvn test -Dgroups=fast -q
if [ $? -ne 0 ]; then
  echo "Fast tests failed. Commit blocked."
  exit 1
fi
```

## Backward-Compatible API Evolution: Expand-Contract Pattern

### Phase 1 — Expand: Add Field as Optional (deploy immediately, no client changes)

```java
// Request DTO — nullable default keeps old clients working
public record CreateOrderRequest(
    @NotBlank String productId,
    @NotNull BigDecimal quantity,
    @Nullable CustomerTier customerTier  // null = legacy client; default to BRONZE
) {
    public CustomerTier effectiveTier() {
        return customerTier != null ? customerTier : CustomerTier.BRONZE;
    }
}
```

```java
// Controller — v1 and v2 share the same handler, tier defaults for missing field
@RestController
public class OrderController {

    // v1 endpoint — existing clients unchanged
    @PostMapping("/v1/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> createOrderV1(@Valid @RequestBody CreateOrderRequest req) {
        // customerTier will be null from v1 clients → defaults to BRONZE
        return createOrder(req);
    }

    // v2 endpoint — enforces customerTier is present
    @PostMapping("/v2/orders")
    public ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> createOrderV2(
            @Valid @RequestBody @NotNull CreateOrderRequest req) {
        if (req.customerTier() == null) {
            return ResponseEntity.badRequest()
                .body(new ErrorResponse("customerTier is required in v2"));
        }
        return createOrder(req);
    }

    private ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> createOrder(CreateOrderRequest req) {
        Order order = orderService.create(
            req.productId(), req.quantity(), req.effectiveTier()
        );
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(OrderResponse.from(order));
    }
}
```

### Phase 2 — Deprecation Headers on v1 (RFC 8594)

```java
@Component
public class DeprecationHeaderFilter implements Filter {
    @Override
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest req, ServletResponse res, FilterChain chain)
            throws IOException, ServletException {
        chain.doFilter(req, res);
        HttpServletResponse response = (HttpServletResponse) res;
        String path = ((HttpServletRequest) req).getRequestURI();
        if (path.startsWith("/v1/")) {
            response.setHeader("Deprecation", "true");
            response.setHeader("Sunset", "Sat, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 GMT");
            response.setHeader("Link", "</v2/orders>; rel=\"successor-version\"");
        }
    }
}
```

Response headers sent to all v1 clients:
```http
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
Deprecation: true
Sunset: Sat, 01 Jan 2026 00:00:00 GMT
Link: </v2/orders>; rel="successor-version"
```

### Phase 3 — Monitor v1 Usage, Coordinate Migration

```java
// Track which clients are still using v1 after deprecation notice
@Aspect
@Component
public class ApiVersionAuditAspect {
    @Around("@annotation(org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PostMapping)")
    public Object auditVersion(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp) throws Throwable {
        HttpServletRequest req = ((ServletRequestAttributes)
            RequestContextHolder.getRequestAttributes()).getRequest();
        String version = extractVersion(req.getRequestURI());
        meterRegistry.counter("api.calls",
            "version", version,
            "client", req.getHeader("X-Client-ID")
        ).increment();
        return pjp.proceed();
    }
}
```

```
Grafana dashboard: "v1 API callers" query
  2025-01: mobile-app → 0 calls (migrated ✅)
  2025-01: web-app    → 0 calls (migrated ✅)
  2025-01: enterprise-client-A → 12,450 calls  ← still on v1, needs nudge
```

### Phase 4 — Contract (Enforce) After All Clients Migrated

```java
// After all clients confirmed on v2, remove v1 endpoint (or return 410 Gone)
@PostMapping("/v1/orders")
public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> createOrderV1Retired() {
    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.GONE)
        .body(new ErrorResponse("v1 API retired. Migrate to /v2/orders"));
}
```

followUps.answer:
**URL versioning** — easier to test in a browser, explicit in logs and metrics, simple to route at the gateway level. Preferred for public APIs and mobile clients where cache-ability matters (URLs are the cache key).

**Header versioning** (content negotiation) — keeps URLs clean, aligns with HTTP semantics (representation negotiation), preferred for internal APIs and when you want clients to explicitly request a format.

```java
// Header versioning with Spring content negotiation
@GetMapping(value = "/orders/{id}",
    produces = "application/vnd.company.order.v2+json")
public OrderV2Response getOrderV2(@PathVariable String id) { ... }

@GetMapping(value = "/orders/{id}",
    produces = "application/vnd.company.order.v1+json")
public OrderV1Response getOrderV1(@PathVariable String id) { ... }
```

Client sends: `Accept: application/vnd.company.order.v2+json`

**Rule of thumb:** URL versioning for external/public APIs (tooling, caching, discoverability); header versioning for internal services where you control all clients. Never use query params (`?version=2`) — they're cacheable inconsistently and semantically wrong.

