## REST → gRPC Decision Framework

### When gRPC Wins

```
✅ High-frequency internal service calls (>10k/min): HTTP/2 multiplexing removes per-request
   TCP handshake overhead
✅ Strict schema contracts needed: proto IDL prevents drift between teams
✅ Bidirectional streaming: real-time data feeds (telemetry, chat, event streaming)
✅ Multi-language microservices: proto generates type-safe clients in Java, Go, Python
✅ Bandwidth-sensitive: proto binary ~5-7x smaller than equivalent JSON
```

### When to Stay on REST

```
❌ Browser clients: gRPC-Web requires a proxy (Envoy) — operational overhead
❌ Public APIs: REST is universally understood; proto requires generated SDKs
❌ Team unfamiliar with proto toolchain: learning curve slows delivery for 4-6 weeks
❌ Heavy debugging needed: binary format is not human-readable; curl doesn't work
❌ Mature REST codebase with good OpenAPI specs: the contracts already exist
```

### Decision Table for Your Scenario (200k calls/min)

```
Factor                    REST (Current)        gRPC (Proposed)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Connection overhead       High (TCP per req)    Low (HTTP/2 mux)
Payload size              ~800B JSON avg        ~120B proto avg
Latency p99 (expected)    12ms                  4ms
Schema enforcement        OpenAPI (optional)    Proto (compile-time)
Browser compatibility     ✅ Native             ❌ Needs gRPC-Web
Debugging                 curl, Postman         grpcurl, Kreya
Observability             Standard HTTP codes   gRPC codes (needs mapping)
Team ramp-up              0 weeks               4-6 weeks
```

### Implementation: OrderService → InventoryService via gRPC

```protobuf
// inventory.proto
syntax = "proto3";
package com.example.inventory;

service InventoryService {
  rpc CheckStock(StockRequest) returns (StockResponse);
  rpc WatchStock(StockRequest) returns (stream StockEvent);  // server streaming
}

message StockRequest {
  string product_id = 1;  // field numbers are stable — NEVER reuse
  int32  quantity    = 2;
}

message StockResponse {
  bool   in_stock    = 1;
  int32  available   = 2;
  string reserved_id = 3;
}
```

```java
// Server (inventory-service)
@GrpcService
public class InventoryGrpcService extends InventoryServiceGrpc.InventoryServiceImplBase {
    @Override
    public void checkStock(StockRequest request, StreamObserver<StockResponse> observer) {
        try {
            int available = inventoryRepository.getAvailable(request.getProductId());
            observer.onNext(StockResponse.newBuilder()
                .setInStock(available >= request.getQuantity())
                .setAvailable(available)
                .build());
            observer.onCompleted();
        } catch (Exception e) {
            observer.onError(Status.INTERNAL
                .withDescription(e.getMessage()).asRuntimeException());
        }
    }
}
```

```java
// Client (order-service)
@Component
public class InventoryGrpcClient {
    private final InventoryServiceGrpc.InventoryServiceBlockingStub stub;

    public InventoryGrpcClient(ManagedChannel channel) {
        this.stub = InventoryServiceGrpc.newBlockingStub(channel)
            .withDeadlineAfter(500, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);  // always set deadline
    }

    public boolean isInStock(String productId, int quantity) {
        try {
            StockResponse response = stub.checkStock(StockRequest.newBuilder()
                .setProductId(productId).setQuantity(quantity).build());
            return response.getInStock();
        } catch (StatusRuntimeException e) {
            if (e.getStatus().getCode() == Status.Code.DEADLINE_EXCEEDED) {
                log.warn("Inventory service timeout for product={}", productId);
                return false;  // graceful degradation
            }
            throw new InventoryServiceException(e);
        }
    }
}
```

### Proto Schema Evolution Rules

```protobuf
// SAFE: add new optional fields with new field numbers
message StockResponse {
  bool   in_stock     = 1;  // existing — never remove
  int32  available    = 2;  // existing
  string reserved_id  = 3;  // existing
  string warehouse_id = 4;  // NEW — old clients ignore unknown fields (proto3 default)
}

// BREAKING (never do):
// - Reuse field number 3 for a different field
// - Change field type (int32 → string)
// - Remove a field without marking reserved

message StockResponse {
  reserved 3;             // reserve deleted field numbers
  reserved "reserved_id"; // reserve deleted field names
}
```

### Migration Strategy: Strangler Fig for RPC

```
Week 1-2:  Add gRPC alongside REST (both endpoints live)
Week 3-4:  Route 10% traffic to gRPC, monitor error rates and latency
Week 5-6:  Route 100% to gRPC after p99 latency confirmed < 5ms
Week 7:    Remove REST endpoint from inventory-service
Week 8+:   Migrate next service pair
```

followUps.answer:
gRPC has its own 16 status codes (OK, INVALID_ARGUMENT, NOT_FOUND, INTERNAL, DEADLINE_EXCEEDED, etc.). Your existing HTTP dashboards won't see them automatically.

**Step 1 — Map gRPC status codes to your monitoring system:**

```java
// Micrometer gRPC interceptor — wraps all calls with metrics
@Configuration
public class GrpcMetricsConfig {
    @Bean
    public ServerInterceptor metricsInterceptor(MeterRegistry registry) {
        return MetricCollectingServerInterceptor.newBuilder(registry)
            .withLatencyTimer(Timer.builder("grpc.server.duration")
                .percentiles(0.5, 0.95, 0.99))
            .build();
    }
}
```

**Step 2 — Alert on gRPC error codes:**

```yaml
# Prometheus alert: gRPC error rate
groups:
  - name: grpc-slos
    rules:
      - alert: GrpcErrorRateHigh
        expr: |
          rate(grpc_server_duration_count{grpc_status!="OK"}[5m]) /
          rate(grpc_server_duration_count[5m]) > 0.01
        annotations:
          summary: "gRPC error rate > 1%: {{ $labels.grpc_service }}.{{ $labels.grpc_method }}"
```

**Step 3 — Distributed tracing:** use OpenTelemetry Java agent — it instruments gRPC automatically via `GrpcTelemetry`. Trace spans show gRPC service/method, status, and latency in Jaeger alongside your HTTP spans.

**Neither sharing the database nor synchronous calls** — both violate service independence.

**Solution: Event-driven denormalization.** When a user's name changes, user-service publishes a `UserProfileUpdated` event. Order-service consumes it and stores a local copy of the data it needs:

```java
// order-service: local read model of customer data it owns
@Entity
public class CustomerSnapshot {
    @Id private String customerId;
    private String displayName;   // denormalized copy from user-service
    private String email;
    private LocalDateTime lastSyncedAt;
}

@KafkaListener(topics = "user.profile.updated")
public void onUserUpdated(UserProfileUpdated event) {
    customerSnapshotRepository.save(new CustomerSnapshot(
        event.userId(), event.displayName(), event.email(), Instant.now()
    ));
}
```

The invoice uses `CustomerSnapshot.displayName` — no cross-service call at read time. Data is **eventually consistent** but order-service is fully autonomous. This is the standard pattern: each service owns its own data and subscribes to events to stay current.

