## Zero-Downtime Migration: Expand-Contract in 4 Flyway Scripts

### Phase 1 — Expand: Add Nullable Column (Zero table lock in PostgreSQL 11+)

```sql
-- V20250115__add_customer_tier_nullable.sql
-- PostgreSQL 11+ adds column with constant DEFAULT without rewriting the table
-- This runs in milliseconds regardless of table size
ALTER TABLE orders
  ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS customer_tier VARCHAR(10)
  DEFAULT 'BRONZE';
  -- NOT NULL not added yet — existing rows get BRONZE as the implicit default

-- Verify: existing rows have the default
SELECT customer_tier, COUNT(*) FROM orders GROUP BY customer_tier;
-- customer_tier | count
-- BRONZE        | 500000000  ← all existing rows
```

### Phase 2 — Application Code: Write New Column (Deploy, no migration yet)

```java
// JPA entity — write new column on every INSERT/UPDATE
@Entity
@Table(name = "orders")
public class Order {
    @Column(name = "customer_tier")
    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
    private CustomerTier customerTier = CustomerTier.BRONZE;  // safe default for old rows

    // Spring Data now writes customer_tier on every save()
    // New rows: correct tier; existing rows updated when touched
}
```

```java
// OrderService — derive tier from business logic on create
@Transactional
public Order createOrder(CreateOrderRequest req) {
    Customer customer = customerService.getById(req.customerId());
    Order order = new Order(req);
    order.setCustomerTier(customer.getTier());  // set explicitly
    return orderRepository.save(order);
}
```

### Phase 3 — Backfill: Update Existing Rows in Batches

```java
// Backfill job: update 10,000 rows at a time, with sleep to avoid I/O storm
@Component
public class CustomerTierBackfillJob {

    @Scheduled(cron = "0 2 * * * *")  // runs at 2 AM daily until done
    @Transactional
    public void backfill() {
        long lastId = getLastProcessedId();
        int batchSize = 10_000;
        int updated;
        do {
            updated = jdbcTemplate.update("""
                UPDATE orders o
                SET customer_tier = (
                    SELECT tier FROM customers c WHERE c.id = o.customer_id
                )
                WHERE o.id > ?
                  AND o.id <= ? + ?
                  AND o.customer_tier = 'BRONZE'  -- only rows not yet explicitly set
                """, lastId, lastId, batchSize);

            lastId += batchSize;
            saveProgress(lastId);
            log.info("Backfilled up to id={}, rows updated={}", lastId, updated);

            // Throttle: 50ms sleep between batches to limit I/O impact
            Thread.sleep(50);
        } while (updated > 0);
    }
}
```

```bash
# Monitor backfill progress
SELECT
    customer_tier,
    COUNT(*) as count,
    ROUND(100.0 * COUNT(*) / SUM(COUNT(*)) OVER (), 2) AS pct
FROM orders
GROUP BY customer_tier;

# Output at 60% complete:
# customer_tier | count      | pct
# BRONZE        | 200000000  | 40.0  ← still BRONZE default, not yet backfilled
# GOLD          | 120000000  | 24.0
# SILVER        | 130000000  | 26.0
# BRONZE (real) |  50000000  | 10.0  ← confirmed BRONZE customers
```

### Phase 4 — Contract: Enforce NOT NULL After Backfill Complete

```sql
-- V20250215__enforce_customer_tier_not_null.sql
-- Only run after backfill is 100% complete and verified

-- Step 1: Validate constraint exists without locking (PostgreSQL)
ALTER TABLE orders
  ADD CONSTRAINT orders_customer_tier_not_null
  CHECK (customer_tier IS NOT NULL)
  NOT VALID;  -- marks invalid rows, does NOT scan table — instant

-- Step 2: Validate the constraint by scanning (lower lock level than NOT NULL)
ALTER TABLE orders VALIDATE CONSTRAINT orders_customer_tier_not_null;
-- This does a full scan but only holds ShareUpdateExclusiveLock, not AccessExclusiveLock
-- Reads and writes still work during this scan

-- Step 3: Only after VALIDATE completes, set NOT NULL (instant — constraint already proven)
ALTER TABLE orders ALTER COLUMN customer_tier SET NOT NULL;

-- Step 4: Create index concurrently (reads/writes unblocked during index build)
CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_customer_tier ON orders(customer_tier);
```

### Timeline Summary

```
Week 1: Phase 1 — ALTER TABLE ADD COLUMN (milliseconds, zero downtime)
Week 1: Phase 2 — Deploy app code that writes new column (rolling deploy)
Week 2-6: Phase 3 — Backfill runs nightly, ~80M rows/night at 10k/50ms
Week 7: Phase 4 — Verify backfill complete → enforce NOT NULL → create index
Total: zero downtime, zero table locks, live reads/writes throughout
```

