The backfill must be **idempotent** — running it twice on the same rows must produce the same result without corruption.

```java
// Idempotent backfill: uses WHERE customer_tier IS NULL or WHERE customer_tier = 'DEFAULT'
// (never touches rows already explicitly set)
jdbcTemplate.update("""
    UPDATE orders o
    SET customer_tier = (SELECT tier FROM customers c WHERE c.id = o.customer_id)
    WHERE o.id BETWEEN :startId AND :endId
      AND o.customer_tier IS NULL  -- only rows not yet backfilled
    """, params);

// Track progress in a dedicated table so restart continues from last good batch
@Entity @Table(name = "migration_progress")
public class MigrationProgress {
    @Id private String migrationId;  // e.g., "customer_tier_backfill"
    private Long lastProcessedId;    // saved after each successful batch
    private LocalDateTime updatedAt;
}
```

On restart, load `lastProcessedId` from `migration_progress` and continue from there. Each batch is committed independently — a failure only requires replaying the last in-progress batch, not the entire 500M rows.

